{"title_page": "William Ruthven, 1st Earl of Gowrie", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n'''William Ruthven, 1st Earl of Gowrie, 4th Lord of Ruthven''' (c. 1541 \u2013 May 1584) was a [[Peerage of Scotland|Scottish peer]] known for devising the [[Raid of Ruthven]].\n\n==Life and career==\nWilliam Ruthven was born in 1541 in Ruthven Castle, [[Perthshire]], [[Scotland]], the son of [[Patrick Ruthven, 3rd Lord Ruthven]].<ref name=geni>{{cite web|title=William Ruthven (c.1541 - 1584)|url=http://www.geni.com/people/William-Ruthven-1st-Earl-of-Gowrie/6000000006444323538|publisher=geni.com|accessdate=15 February 2014}}</ref>  On 23 August 1581, he was named [[Earl of Gowrie]] by James VI of Scotland.<ref name=be>http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1385082/Ruthven-family</ref>\n\nIn 1582 Ruthven devised and undertook the [[Raid of Ruthven]] - a plot to seize the fifteen-year-old [[James VI and I|James VI]] during the king's visit to his home at Hunting-tower Castle. Ruthven was the last-known custodian of the silver casket that contained the [[Casket letters|Casket Letters]]; letters said to have been written by [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], implicating her in the murder of her husband, [[Henry Stuart, Lord Darnley]].<ref>[https://archive.org/details/correspondenceof00bowerich/page/236 ''Bowes Correspondence''(Surtees Society, 1842)], pp. 236\u20137, Robert Bowes to Francis Cunningham, 8 November 1582.</ref>\n\nIn May 1584 Ruthven was detained, tried, and beheaded at [[Stirling Castle]] because of his leading involvement in the [[Raid of Ruthven]] and all of his honors were forfeited. Following his execution, his lands were divided among the king's favourites.<ref name=geni />  A letter produced in the [[posthumous trial]] of Robert Logan of Restalrig in 1609 referred to William as ''[[Greysteil]]'', a character in a popular poem of his time noted for his strength and sinister powers.<ref>''Acts of the Parliaments of Scotland'', vol. iv, p.422.</ref>\n\n===Marriage and children===\nWilliam Ruthven was married to Dorothea Stewart, the oldest daughter of [[Henry Stewart, 1st Lord Methven]] and Janet Stewart, daughter of [[John Stewart, 2nd Earl of Atholl]]. William and Dorothea had at least 14 children, ten daughters and four sons including:<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul|title=The Scots peerage; founded on Wood's edition of Sir Robert Douglas's peerage of Scotland; containing an historical and genealogical account of the nobility of that kingdom|last=Paul|first=James Balfour|date=1904|publisher=Edinburgh : D. Douglas}}</ref>\n* Jean Ruthven, wife of [[James Ogilvy, 1st Earl of Airlie]]\n* [[Barbara Ruthven]], lady in waiting to [[Anne of Denmark]]\n* Beatrix Ruthven, lady in waiting to Anne of Denmark, wife of John Home of Cowdenknowes.\n* Lilias (or Sophie) Ruthven (d. 1591), first wife of [[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox]]\n* Margaret Ruthven, married to John Graham, 4th Earl of Montrose, mother of [[James Graham, 1st Marquess of Montrose]]\n* Elizabeth \"Isabel\" Ruthven, wife of Sir Robert Gordon, mother of [[John Gordon, 1st Viscount of Kenmure]]\n* Elizabeth Ruthven (d. 1617), second wife of Sir Hugh Campbell of Loudon (d. 1622).<ref>James Paterson, ''History of the counties of Ayr and Wigton: Cunninghame'', vol. 3 part 2 (Edinburgh, 1866), pp. 548-9.</ref>\n* James Ruthven, 2nd Earl of Gowrie (d. 1588)\n* [[John Ruthven, 3rd Earl of Gowrie]] (c. 1577 \u2013 5 August 1600)\n* [[Alexander Ruthven]] (12 January 1580 - 5 August 1600)\n* William Ruthven, died in France prior to 1622<ref>{{Cite book|title=Blood of Kings|last=Davies|first=J.D.|publisher=Ian Allan Publishing|year=2010|isbn=9780711035263|location=England|pages=76}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catalogue.nrscotland.gov.uk/nrsonlinecatalogue/details.aspx?reference=GD246/75&st=1&tc=y&tl=n&tn=n&tp=n&k=gowrie&ko=a&r=&ro=s&df=&dt=&di=y|title=NAS Catalogue - catalogue record|last=Scotland|first=National Archives of|website=catalogue.nrscotland.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref>\n* Patrick Ruthven, imprisoned for 19 years in the [[Tower of London]]\n\nJohn and Alexander were killed on 5 August 1600 as the main characters in [[Gowrie conspiracy|The Gowrie Conspiracy]], a failed attempt to kidnap or murder [[James VI and I|James VI]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n*{{EB1911 |first=Ronald John |last=McNeill |wstitle=Gowrie, John Ruthven, 3rd Earl of |volume=12 |pages=301\u2013302}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite DNB |first=Thomas Finlayson |last=Henderson |wstitle=Ruthven, William (1541?-1584)|display=Ruthven, William (1541?\u20131584) |volume=50 |pages=25\u201329 |short=x}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{s-new|creation}}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl of Gowrie]]\n       | years  = 1581\u20131584 }}\n{{s-aft| rows   = 2 | after  = [[James Ruthven, 2nd Earl of Gowrie|James Ruthven]] }}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Patrick Ruthven, 3rd Lord Ruthven|Patrick Ruthven]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Earl of Gowrie#Lords Ruthven (1488)|Lord Ruthven]]\n       | years  = 1566\u20131584 }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gowrie, William Ruthven, 1st Earl Of}}\n[[Category:1540s births]]\n[[Category:1584 deaths]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:Earls of Gowrie|William]]\n[[Category:Executed Scottish people]]\n[[Category:People executed for treason against Scotland]]\n[[Category:16th-century executions by Scotland]]\n[[Category:Treasurers of Scotland]]\n[[Category:People executed by the Kingdom of Scotland by decapitation]]\n[[Category:Scottish politicians convicted of crimes]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n'''William Ruthven, 1st Earl of Gowrie, 4th Lord of Ruthven''' (c. 1541 \u2013 May 1584) was a [[Peerage of Scotland|Scottish peer]] known for devising the [[Raid of Ruthven]].\n\n==Life and career==\nWilliam Ruthven was born in 1541 in Ruthven Castle, [[Perthshire]], [[Scotland]], the son of [[